{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567664","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567664"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:05:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:05:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19226"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19226","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19226"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.34,0.07,0.19,0.23,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11960"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107954"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11960","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11960"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19226"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90367"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2295"},{"type":"tags","id":"2746"},{"type":"tags","id":"2970"},{"type":"tags","id":"2971"},{"type":"tags","id":"3870"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"28063"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37528"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107954","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107954"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of uncomfortable sensations in her legs that occur in the evenings. She describes an occasional urge to move her legs when sitting or lying down, which temporarily relieves the discomfort. The symptoms are worse at night and occasionally interfere with her sleep. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination of her lower limbs is unremarkable. Blood tests reveal haemoglobin 128 g/L (115-155), mean corpuscular volume 88 fL (80-100), ferritin 22 \u03bcg/L (15-200), vitamin B12 380 ng/L (200-600), folate 12 \u03bcg/L (3-20), and thyroid stimulating hormone 3.1 mU/L (0.5-4.0).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral iron supplementation","Levodopa with carbidopa","Gabapentin","Magnesium supplementation","Pramipexole"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of restless legs syndrome (RLS): an urge to move the legs that worsens during periods of rest, is temporarily relieved by movement, and occurs predominantly in the evening or night. Her symptoms are relatively mild. The ferritin level of 22 \u03bcg/L, while within the laboratory reference range, is below the recommended threshold of 50 \u03bcg/L for patients with RLS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral iron supplementation\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial treatment. Current guidelines recommend maintaining ferritin levels above 50 \u03bcg/L in patients with RLS, as iron deficiency can both cause and aggravate symptoms. Iron is a cofactor for tyrosine hydroxylase, which is essential for dopamine synthesis in the brain. Even with ferritin levels in the lower normal range, iron supplementation often leads to symptom improvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELevodopa with carbidopa\u003C/strong\u003E can be used for RLS when lifestyle changes and iron supplementation are insufficient. For mild and infrequent limb movements at sleep onset, levodopa with carbidopa 100+25 to 200+50 mg orally before bedtime when needed may be prescribed. The maximum dose for RLS is lower than that used in Parkinson disease. This would be considered if maintaining ferritin above 50 \u03bcg/L doesn\u0027t provide adequate symptom relief.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGabapentin\u003C/strong\u003E is an effective treatment for moderate to severe RLS and may be particularly useful in patients with comorbid pain or anxiety. However, given this patient\u0027s mild symptoms and suboptimal ferritin level, addressing potential iron deficiency is the more appropriate first step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnesium supplementation\u003C/strong\u003E has limited evidence for efficacy in RLS. While some patients report benefit, it would not be appropriate as initial therapy, particularly when there is a clear indication for iron supplementation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPramipexole\u003C/strong\u003E is a dopamine agonist that can be effective for RLS but is now reserved for patients with more severe symptoms who do not respond to other treatments. Long-term use carries a risk of augmentation and impulse control disorders.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMost cases of RLS are mild and may respond to lifestyle modifications alone, including regular physical exercise, good sleep hygiene, and avoiding caffeine and alcohol. However, this patient\u0027s ferritin level below 50 \u03bcg/L provides a clear indication for iron supplementation as the initial intervention, which may resolve her symptoms without the need for other medications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Restless legs syndrome is characterised by an urge to move the legs that worsens at rest and improves with movement, occurring predominantly in the evening or night.","Iron supplementation is recommended when ferritin levels are below 50 \u03bcg/L in patients with restless legs syndrome.","Most mild cases of restless legs syndrome can be managed with lifestyle modifications including regular exercise and good sleep hygiene."],"references":["Nanayakkara B, Di Michiel J, Yee BJ. Restless legs syndrome. Aust J Gen Pract. 2023;52(9):613\u2013618. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2023/september/restless-legs-syndrome"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90367"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19226"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90367","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90367"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-05T10:45:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-05T10:46:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11960"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107954"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":